{
  "title": "COSPs",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c20f627e5ebfad23",
      "text": "This page is a first attempt to define Computer-Supported Patterns (COSPs). The proposed structure is based on the following goals:"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "1c945f81a4e54c35",
      "text": "<ul><li><b>Open and decentralized.</b> It should be possible for experts to publish their patterns without the need for a central authority to approve them. Rigorous user-controlled trust mechanisms come here to complement informal trust in the repository manager that is the basis of centralized schemes. Additionally, mechanisms for pattern identification, retrieval, tracing (versioning, composition, etc.) provenance and navigation must be provided. </li>"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "047e49292702e7f6",
      "text": "<ul><li><b>Machine-processable.</b> Patterns should be designed to be treated by computer-assisted means for their creation, publishing, evolution, browsing/searching and cataloguing, but also to facilitate advanced forms of use such as their  integration in modeling and development environments. An important short-term advantage of this is that it allows the creation of an online distributed catalog of patterns with advanced searching and browsing capabilities, as well as reference-based and feature-based navigation. In addition to this, the management of patterns as complex objects with advanced presentation capabilities (such as for instance condensing or expanding sections, using different views, etc.) will represent an advance that is easy to achieve but very valuable in practice.\n</li>"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "7647d6f8cdc7467f",
      "text": "<ul><li><b>Detailed and precise.</b> Patterns must allow experts to capture a rich set of characteristics and details with enough rigor and precision to suit the needs of different users and scenarios but without sacrificing their generality, which is necessary in order to ensure their reusability. In order to achieve this, both syntax and semantics of patterns need to be redefined to ensure that patterns produced by different sources are comparable and understandable. We believe that ontological support can be the basis to achieve this goal. In principle, ontological support can help improving selection capabilities, and interoperability of patterns from different sources. The approach we propose to follow is based on previous results on secure decentralized ontologies, which can easily be adapted to JSON. In essence, the idea is to allow the inclusion of references to external \"ontologies\" in different fields of the patters. As a simple example, the security properties provided by a security pattern could be related using external ontologies. Assume the “Authentication” property provided by the “Credential” pattern has the following relations to other properties:\n“Authentication” equals “Client Authentication”\n“Mutual Authentication” implies “Client Authentication”\nIn this way, a search for a pattern providing the “Authentication” property would return all patterns providing any of the “Authentication”, “Client Authentication” or “Mutual Authentication” properties, as all of them could fit the original goal of the developer. Of course, pattern search mechanisms should provide flexible interfaces allowing system engineers to decide if ontology-supported equivalence is used or not in a given query. Another example in the security domain is using ontologies to relate threats to actual attacks. Finally, ontologies become an essential tool in order to ensure that patterns provided by different entities can be understood and compared. \n</li>"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "fd2fe42b6580b2bd",
      "text": "<ul><li><b>Engineering-oriented.</b> In addition to current documentation-oriented or education-oriented patterns, the new version should enable a tighter integration in engineering activities and processes, facilitating the tasks of adopting a security pattern in a System Under Development (SUD). Therefore, as a necessary complement to the evolved patterns, we need to enhance existing processes and methodologies that use them and maybe find new ones. \n</li>"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "35ef859ec1a87d57",
      "text": "<ul><li><b>Trusted.</b> Trust management mechanisms should be a core element in the new patterns so that developers can use patterns validated by actors (individuals, organizations...) they trust, with guarantees of authenticity, integrity and with reliable assessment of their quality and reputation. Therefore, we propose the inclusion of mechanisms guaranteeing the quality and integrity of the pattern. This is related to the concept of provenance in the sense that it covers origin and authorship, but also the aspects of reuse, adaptation and extension, also inherent to provenance. Of course, relations between patterns must be considered. Additionally, we believe it would be useful to have mechanisms for associating some sort of “reputation” (i.e. community-based evaluation) to the patterns, but this should be done independently to the pattern content. In this context, the concept of \"Endorsement\" can be a valid solution as it allows trust to be based on actors other than the pattern creator.</li>\n</ul>"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5362c1153e03a90e",
      "text": "For a more precise definition of the structure see the [[Semi-formal specification of COSPs structure]], where the JSON schema is described using [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extended_Backus%E2%80%93Naur_Form#Table_of_symbols EBNF] for easy understanding by readers. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "91edf407508a88e1",
      "text": "I'm also working on [[a more formal specification for COSPs based on the Federated Wiki]] described using [http://json-schema.org/ JSON Schema]."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "d94377afb80cc51b",
      "text": "The structure is described using an example here: [[COSP Example Structure]]. Note that the proposed structure should fit within the standard \"Story\" element of a federated wiki page. The only adition to the standard format is the inclusion of the \"endorsement\" element as part of the definition of the \"Journal\" section of the pages. I believe this should be incorporated in the standard since it transcends the current initiative to define COSPs, allowing other uses, and enabling the creation of what we could call the \"trusted federated wiki\".<br><br><br>"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4bd2974719d6c559",
      "text": " "
